Translation:
"The Cool Girls Now are Feminists": Why Young Women Are Supporting Feminism

The number of young women who call themselves "feminists" is increasing. Feminism is regarded positively. It's cool. That's the scene. We present to you an article published in the 9/30/2019 issue of AERA. 

***
"Akko Akko Gorilla, Akko Akko Gorilla..."

"The M/ALL" is an event that ties together themes of music, art, and society. A large crowd packed rapper Akko Gorilla-san's concert. Her Twitter profile proclaims her a "feminist." A song representative of her work, "GRRLISM," contains the lyric "my body my choice."

Although it's been discussed in the English-speaking world, translator Nonaka Momo-san wrote in her postscript to Roxane Gay's <i>Bad Feminist</i>:

"In the 2010s, especially in the last few years, in media aimed at young women, you can feel the trend that 'all cool girls are feminists.'" (<i>Bad Feminist</i> Akishobo, Inc., page 388). 

There are many definitions of "feminism," but to keep it simple, let's use "thoughts and actions that realize a society without discrimination based on sex." The number of people who agree with feminist assertions with the caveat, "but I'm not a feminist" has decreased. There was an association like "I agree with the statement. But I don't want people to think I'm a feminist. Because feminists seem like angry man haters..." However, now, in the younger generation, the number of young women who boldly wear the label "feminist" has increased.

One background factor may be what one might call "celebrity feminist proclamations." In 2013, the popular American singer Beyoncé (38) sampled part of Nigerian author Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie's (42) speech "We Should All Be Feminists" in the song "Flawless." In 2014, the British actress Emma Watson (29), most famous for playing Hermione in the "Harry Potter" movie series, stood on stage at the United Nations and said she was a feminist.
